                  <interp inst="t18210606-34-crimeloc199" type="placeName" value="Fish-street-hill"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18210606-34-crimeloc199" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18210606-34-off197 t18210606-34-crimeloc199"></join>, and am a <rs id="t18210606-34-viclabel200" type="occupation">confectioner</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18210606-34-victim386 t18210606-34-viclabel200"></join>. The prisoner came into my shop on the 24th of April (I had seen him three weeks before), and asked for change for a sovereign. I called my servant up, counted 20 s., and said</p>
               <p>"Give it to him, and take care how you deliver it." I stood looking through the back parlour window - she gave him the 20 s. - he said to the servant, I want a half-sovereign - she said she had none. He then said the change would not do, and returned her the change - she counted it, and brought it to me - there was only 15 s. I told him it was the second time he had tried to rob me - he had kept ten sixpences back. I sent for a constable, he shifted the ten sixpences out of his sleeve, and said,</p>
               <p>"Here is the rest of your change."</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. BRODERICK. Q. You kept the sovereign after he returned the change - A. Yes.</p>
               <p>COURT. Then you had value for it.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18210606-34-verdict201" type="verdictDescription">
